05139nam a22007935i 9780823291021DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232910217 a10.1515/97808232910212doi  a(DE-B1597)565966  a(OCoLC)1306541927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aBetter Off Dead :bThe Evolution of the Zombie as Post-Human /ced. by Sarah Juliet Lauro, Deborah Christie. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe zombie is ubiquitous in popular culture: from comic books to video games, to internet applications and homemade films, zombies are all around us. Investigating the zombie from an interdisciplinary perspective, with an emphasis on deep analytical engagement with diverse kinds of texts, Better Off Dead addresses some of the more unlikely venues where zombies are found while providing the reader with a classic overview of the zombie’s folkloric and cinematic history. What has the zombie metaphor meant in the past? Why does it continue to be so prevalent in our culture? Where others have looked at the zombie as an allegory for humanity’s inner machinations or claimed the zombie as capitalist critique, this collection seeks to provide an archaeology of the zombie—tracing its lineage from Haiti, mapping its various cultural transformations, and suggesting the post-humanist direction in which the zombie is ultimately heading. Approaching the zombie from many different points of view, the contributors look across history and across media. Though they represent various theoretical perspectives, the whole makes a cohesive argument: The zombie has not just evolved within narratives; it has evolved in a way that transforms narrative. This collection announces a new post-zombie, even before the boundaries of this rich and mysterious myth have been completely charted.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBond, Elson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoon, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCollins, Margo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegoul, Franck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDendle, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFhlainn, Sorcha Ní, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKee, Chera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLauro, Sarah Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLauro, Sarah Juliet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeaux, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuntean, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Bernice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPifer, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZani, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329102140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter